SIMPLE: ensign
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: ensign
<hw>en"sign</hw> <pr>(⟦ecr⟧n"s⟦icr⟧n <it>also</it> ⟦ecr⟧n"s⟦imac⟧n,
except for 4a)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>enseigne</ets>, L.
<ets>insignia</ets>, pl. of <ets>insigne</ets> a distinctive mark,
badge, flag; <ets>in + signum</ets> mark, sign. See <er>Sign</er>, and
cf. <er>Insignia</er>, 3d <er>Ancient</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
flag; a banner; a standard; esp., the national flag, or a banner
indicating nationality, carried by a ship or a body of soldiers; -- as
distinguished from flags indicating divisions of the army, rank of naval
officers, or private signals, and the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hang up your <qex>ensigns</qex>, let your drums be still.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A signal displayed like a standard, to give
notice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He will lift an <qex>ensign</qex> to the nations from far.</q>
<rj><qau>Is. v. 26.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Sign; badge of office, rank, or power;
symbol.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>ensigns</qex> of our power about we bear.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Formerly, a commissioned officer of the
army who carried the ensign or flag of a company or regiment.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>A commissioned officer of the lowest grade in the
navy, corresponding to the grade of second lieutenant in the army.</def>
<rj><au>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In the British army the rank of <xex>ensign</xex> was
abolished in 1871. In the United States army the rank is not recognized;
the regimental flags being carried by a sergeant called the <xex>color
sergeant</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ensign bearer</b></col>, <cd>one who carries a flag; an
ensign.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ensign</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ensign
<hw>En"sign</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To designate as by
an ensign.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Henry but joined the roses that <qex>ensigned</qex>⟦br⟧
Particular families.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To distinguish by a mark or ornament; esp.
<fld>(Her.)</fld>, by a crown; <as>thus, any charge which has a crown
immediately above or upon it, is said to be
<ex>ensigned</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ensigncy</ent>⟦br⟧
